se I know that if I say something like, well, I'm uneasy I'm uncomfortable or not feeling great, then my wife's gonna be uneasy and uncomfortable. And if she's uneasy and uncomfortable, the kids are uneasy and no one's having a good time. So usually I just kind of push it deep down inside and try not to think about it. But there's this feeling there that as soon as that sun sets, there's just something wrong. After spending so many years in that country and backpacking in remote areas, I don't feel that anywhere else. Only in this location at these dunes. And the last time we were out there, we're there and it's close to a full moon. The nights were extremely bright. And if you've ever experienced a full moon in the desert where there's no trees and very little ground cover, it's just something different than experiencing that where there's light pollution or there's, you know, heavy forest, everything is whitewashed, everything's just blinded. White shadows and objects are very crisp and defined. So we're there and, you know, darkness falls and that same uneasy feeling comes back. So eventually go to bed, get in the camper and fall asleep. And I remember having this dream where I'm with, you know, the family and we're just standing and off in the distance is this shadowy figure and this just feeling of unease and being uncomfortable and this uncontrollable urge to confront that. And in the dream, I end up running straight towards that shadowy black blob. And, you know, it's dreams day, so everything seems super fast and super slow at the same time. But I'm running towards this object because I feel like I need to get to it. And as soon as I reach it, I wake up and I'm shaky and cold and it felt like a nightmare, but it wasn't a nightmare. And I'm, you know, laying there trying to figure out what that meant and to calm myself down. And I have to pee. So I figured now is a good time. I'm already awake. I'm going to crawl out of camper and go pee. So I make my way and